---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Section from '../../components/Section.astro';
import Button from '../../components/Button.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Revenue Performance Audit"
  description="Measurement integrity, attribution and revenue-loss analysis, and the strategic synthesis that turns three audits into one plan. Finds where your data is lying and where revenue is leaking."
>
  <Section class="pt-28 pb-16">
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center">
      <div class="max-w-2xl">
        <p class="text-accent font-mono text-sm mb-4">The Get Right &rsaquo; Revenue Performance Audit</p>
        <h1 class="mb-6">Revenue Performance Audit</h1>
        <p class="text-accent text-lg font-medium mb-4">Powered by Delphi</p>
        <p class="text-secondary-text text-xl leading-relaxed">
          Measurement integrity, attribution and revenue-loss analysis, and the
          strategic synthesis that ties all three audits together. This is where the
          revenue numbers live &mdash; and where the unified 90-day execution plan is built.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="hidden lg:block">
        <img
          src="/revenue-hero.svg"
          alt=""
          width="520"
          height="440"
          class="w-auto max-h-72 mx-auto"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section elevated>
    <h2 class="mb-8">Four layers of analysis</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-bg-surface border border-border-subtle rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="text-accent text-xl mb-3">Layer 1: Measurement Integrity</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary-text leading-relaxed">
          Can you trust the numbers you're already looking at? We detect every
          analytics and ad tag on the page &mdash; GTM, GA4, Meta, TikTok, Pinterest
          &mdash; and flag duplicates, conflicts, and coverage gaps across your
          templates. Then we confirm your conversion events actually fire, check how
          consent tooling is shaping or blocking what you collect, and weigh your whole
          stack against the ideal for your industry.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-bg-surface border border-border-subtle rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="text-accent text-xl mb-3">Layer 2: Attribution &amp; Revenue Loss</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary-text leading-relaxed">
          Where is revenue leaking out of your measurement? Delphi estimates how much
          of your &ldquo;direct&rdquo; traffic is really misattributed organic, paid,
          and referral &mdash; then traces why: cross-domain checkout breaks,
          ad-blocker and Safari ITP erosion, fragile client-side cookies, and whether
          you have the server-side tracking to survive it. Every gap gets a dollar
          range, and a twelve-month forecast names when your attribution drops below
          the point you can trust.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-bg-surface border border-border-subtle rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="text-accent text-xl mb-3">Layer 3: Connect Your Data</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary-text leading-relaxed">
          Want grounded numbers instead of estimates? The whole audit runs cold
          &mdash; no logins, no access, nothing to install &mdash; which is what makes
          it fast to commission. Bring your own data, though, and it sharpens: a GA4,
          Google Ads, Meta, or Plausible export &mdash; CSV today, a live API on the
          way &mdash; re-grounds every estimate in your real traffic, spend, and
          revenue.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-bg-surface border border-border-subtle rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="text-accent text-xl mb-3">Layer 4: Strategic Synthesis</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary-text leading-relaxed">
          The keystone &mdash; where every finding becomes one plan. We take the
          technical findings from the Platform Audit, the content gaps from the Content
          Audit, and the attribution findings here, and score them together by revenue
          impact, effort, and dependency. The output: one prioritized 90-day roadmap
          across all three pillars, with a revenue projection and KPI checkpoints at
          30, 60, and 90 days.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section>
    <div class="max-w-2xl">
      <h2 class="mb-4">How it connects</h2>
      <p class="text-secondary-text text-lg mb-6">
        This is the pillar the other two feed into. Technical findings arrive from the
        Platform Audit and become dollar amounts; content gaps arrive from the Content
        Audit and get sequenced by conversion potential. What leaves is a single 90-day
        roadmap your team executes against &mdash; not three reports to reconcile.
      </p>
      <p class="text-secondary-text text-lg">
        Without this pillar, you have two backlogs. With it, you have one plan.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section elevated>
    <div class="max-w-2xl">
      <h2 class="mb-4">Why it's called Delphi</h2>
      <p class="text-secondary-text text-lg mb-6">
        The oracle at Delphi never handed pilgrims a pile of omens. They arrived with
        scattered signs and left with one answer, in plain language, about what to do
        next. The three tools divide the work the same way: Muttr makes your site
        discoverable and fast, Canary makes sure visitors find what they came for, and
        Delphi proves whether they actually did. A website without analytics is a black
        box. One with bad analytics is a money pit &mdash; every decision made against
        numbers that were never true.
      </p>
      <p class="text-secondary-text text-lg">
        Delphi is also where everything consolidates. Every ticket Muttr surfaces and
        every gap Canary finds arrives here to be weighed by revenue impact, sequenced
        into a single plan your team can actually run, and tied to the metric that will
        prove whether each fix worked. You don't just leave with a list of what to do
        &mdash; you leave knowing how you'll tell it paid off.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section>
    <div class="text-center">
      <h2 class="mb-4">See the full engagement</h2>
      <p class="text-secondary-text text-lg mb-8 max-w-xl mx-auto">
        The Revenue Performance Audit only reaches its potential when paired with
        the other two pillars. That's why The Get Right runs all three together.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4">
        <Button href="/the-get-right">See The Full Get Right</Button>
        <Button href="/contact" variant="secondary">Talk to a Founder</Button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>
</BaseLayout>
